{102}  Dr. Oliver (in his âReligious houses on the Witham,â appendix pp.
165â167) says: âThe honours of the Witham may be inferred, not only from
the consecrated spots and temples (once existent) on its banks, but from
its very names.  It was called Grant-avon, or the divine stream; and
Cwaith-Ket, _i.e._ the work or river of âKetâ (Ked or Keridwen, the Druid
goddess Ceres).  Ket survives in Catley, not far from the Witham.  The
river was worshipped as her embodiment.  Oliver adds: âThe sacred places
on its banks were more numerous, perhaps than those of any other river in
Britain.â  It will be apparent, to anyone that the name Witham is not a
river name at all, but that of a village, the village near which the
river rises.  In the time of Leland, the antiquary (circa 1550) it was
known as the Lindis.  He says: âThere be four ferys upon the water of
Lindis betwixt Lincoln and Boston.  Shut (Short) Fery, Tatershaul Fery,
Dogdick Fery, Langreth Feryâ (quoted by Mr. G. Sills, Archl. His. Wash.,
âLin. N. and Q.,â Nat. His. section, July, 1897, p. 108).  But Mr. Taylor
tells us (in his âWords and Places,â p. 130) that âthroughout the whole
of England there is hardly a single river name which is not Celtic,â and
accordingly the Celtic name of the Witham was Grant-avon (avon meaning
âriverâ), while the town upon it was Grantham.  It was also known by the
names âRheâ and âAye,â the former Celtic, the latter Saxon or Danish.
âLin. N. and Q.,â vol. ii., p. 222.

