{246}  Referring to these portions of screen, Mr. G. E. Jeans, author of
âMurrayâs Handbook to Lincolnshire,â says âKirkstead Abbey, most valuable
Early English screen, one of the earliest in Englandâ (âLincs. N. & Q.,â
vol. ii., p. 91).  Also Dr. Mansel Sympson, in a Paper on âLincolnshire
Rood Screens,â read before the Architectural Society, June, 1890, goes
into further detail.  He says, âIt is composed of 13 bays.  Each bay
consists of a lancet-headed trefoil, supported by octagonal pillars, with
moulded capitals and bases . . . total height 2ft. 9in.  Some screen-work
exists in Rochester Cathedral of exactly the same character.â  And the
late Mr. Bloxam gave a drawing of a similar specimen in Thurcaston
Church, Leicestershire.  That at Stanton Harcourt, Oxfordshire, is not
quite similar, and is 40 or 50 years later (1260); so that we may be
proud of possessing, at Kirkstead, almost the oldest fragment of work, in
this particular line, in the country.  (âArchitect. Soc. Journ.,â 1890,
pp. 198, 199).

